FIPS 186-x/ANSI x9.31 primality-search sequences

Sequences where an intermediate (probable) prime Y needs to be discarded
since E|Y-1 for public exponent E. Accepting such Y+E would lead to
an invalid RSA keypair, see RFC 8017 3.1, or FIPS 186-5, B.9, step 7
("F1865" below).

See [F1865, B.9], "Compute a probable prime factor based on auxiliary
primes"---referenced by A.1.6, "Generation of probable primes with
conditions based on auxiliary probable primes", as the top-level
RSA-keypair generation spec---for steps of enumerating Y candidates.

r1,r2: auxiliary primes
X: original X from random number generator [F1865, B.9, step 3]
E: public exponent
NP.E: 'non-prime' due to E: candidate in sequence which is a probable
    prime, not to be tested, being +1 mod E [F1865, B.9, step 7]. Since
    NP.E is a probable prime, it would be accepted by the rest of C.9.
Y: first candidate Y returned as probable prime from (X, r1, r2)
   sequence; >NP.E.
NR.Y: number of Y candidates tested with X as original 'random' bytes (>=2)

The sequences below use r1, r2 of 192 bits, a bitcount suitable for
all RSA-prime sizes relevant for FIPS 186-4 [F1864, Table B.1], or 224
bits, for sizes relevant for FIPS 186-5 [F1865, Table A.1]. We expect
implementations to use a single bitcount for all r1/r2, and not select
the minimum for each RSA-modulus size; use of fixed sizes allows for
certain specialization which would benefit all searches.

The original search-start X could be possibly selected as the prime
preceding E in the sequence +1, to maximize the number of candidates
tested (NR.Y).

For each size, we include two examples, one with NP.E and Y close, and
one where they are distant in the (Y, r1, r2) sequences. The close
ones might be fast enough to retain as runtime tests; the distant ones
exercise much of the primality-search infrastructure while finding the
proper Y.
